##Will the United States repeat what happened in Italy with the new crown?

How bad will things get in America? List of Governors of Washington John Jay Easley said on March 10 that the number could reach 64,000 in Washington state alone within two months. That's 16 times the number of confirmed cases in the United States, according to Real time statistics released by the Johns Hopkins University. As of 6 a.m. on March 17, Beijing time, the number of confirmed cases of new pneumonia in the United States had reached 4, 464 cases.

At the time of John Jay Easley's comments, that prediction sounded frightening and unrealistic, as Washington state had only 162 confirmed cases of new pneumonia. But by March 14, the State had confirmed 642 people, showing how quickly the number of confirmed cases had doubled. President Donald Trump announced at the White House on March 13 that the United States had entered a "state of emergency" to deal with a new outbreak of pneumonia, and introduced the latest testing procedures.

If you want to speculate about what might happen in the United States, the worst case scenario is what has already happened in Italy. There have been 27,980 confirmed cases and 2,158 deaths in Italy, and the number continues to rise.

Figure | curve of confirmed cases in Italy (Source: WORLDOMETERS)

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
In a blog post on March 8, Dr. Daniele Macchini, a doctor on the Italian front line of the epidemic, said hospitals were preparing for the early stages of the epidemic, slowly and selectively emptying patients, to create an "air of surreal silence and emptiness that we still don't understand, " that early sense of calm. It feels like preparing for a war that health care workers aren't sure is coming.

But then patients start coming in, and always get the same diagnosis: Bilateral interstitial pneumonia, which attacks the lungs and makes breathing difficult. "people have been advised to stay home with a fever for a week or 10 days with mild symptoms and not go out, which reduces the risk of infection. But until they can't stand it anymore, they start to run out of breath and need oxygen. " So, the intensive-care unit soon filled up.

"War did break out, day and night, " Macchini wrote. "there were no surgeons, urologists, orthopedic surgeons. We were just doctors. " He suddenly became part of a team, to deal with this overwhelming disaster. Because drug therapies for the new coronavirus are limited, treatment depends primarily on the individual's resistance and the hope is that the body will be able to eliminate the virus itself.

As cases multiply, hospital beds are filling up at an alarming rate, and SWAB results keep coming in: positive, positive, positive. "The emergency room just collapsed, " says Macchini, "while there are still people on social networks who pride themselves on not being afraid, ignoring their fears and protesting against restrictions on their normal way of life, the reality is that the epidemic is happening horribly. "

According to WHO data, the overall case-fatality rate for NCP is about 3.5 per cent, although the true figure is uncertain as some cases may be asymptomatic. But in Italy, the figure could be higher than 6 per cent. Part of the reason is that Italy has a population as old as Florida -- the case fatality rate for people over 80 is 1,000 times higher than for people under 20. People over 80 may have an 18 percent chance of dying, according to previous data.

Macchini's article calls for people to keep their distance, stop the gathering to slow the spread of the disease: "share! Share! Share the information. We must announce it to prevent a repeat of what happened in Italy. " This is the story of Italy over the past few weeks, wHAT WILL BE THE STORY OF AMERICA IN THE COMING WEEKS?

So far, doctors have known some of the patterns of transmission of the disease, and the speed at which a viral infection can spread depends on its intrinsic nature and on the opportunities society gives it. Each virus has a so-called base infection number (R0) , which is a measure of how many people an infected person will infect.

Figure | how base infection number (R0) affects disease transmission (Source: Mit Technology Review)

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
Currently, the R0 valuation for COVID-19 is between 2.0 and 2.5. But according to the World Health Organization, that is the best guess. By comparison, the average R0 for the common flu is 1.3; for highly contagious diseases such as measles, R0 is greater than 10. As can be seen from the above table, in theory, the virus could spread rapidly from the first five infected people, although in practice the rate of transmission would gradually slow after a certain number of increases.

Note that the value of R0 is not immutable. Isolating patients and their contacts can effectively change transmission rates. In the case of SARS, which broke out in 2003, similar public health measures were ultimately used to eradicate the virus. Therefore, "social alienation" is the most effective way to slow down the spread of the virus. The number of confirmed cases is multiplying in areas where new coronavirus transmission is uncontrolled and detection capacity is increasing. It's doubling every two days, as it has in Washington this past week.

However, once measures are taken to reduce transmission accordingly, the doubling of confirmed cases will be much slower. In Japan, for example, the number of confirmed cases doubled in 10 days.

To avoid crises in overburdened hospitals, governments and health agencies must take steps to slow the spread of the disease. And this mode of thinking and the UK, Germany and other countries so-called "leveling curve" idea similar. Although most people may eventually catch the virus, the chances are that more lives will be saved as transmission time lengthens, he said. Because it would allow people to be better cared for. Once a hospital is intensive-care unit with patients and does not have enough equipment (breathing machines, for example) to treat them, it can be italy-style, with potentially higher death rates.

Are the tests up to speed?

The head of the World Health Organization has sent a simple message to the world about who should be tested for the new coronavirus: "Test, test, test, test every suspected case. " But according to CNN, although U. S. health officials say the tests are being accelerated and are being run through multiple states, there is still a lack of available tests.

At present, the United States front-line health care workers are counting every breathing machine, each ICU bed, and for the worst case contingency planning. Meanwhile, the head of the White House Coronavirus Task Force, the vice president's Mike Pence and senior health officials are trying to calm a "nervous" nation. They said the testing of the new coronavirus was entering a "new phase" as more than 2,000 laboratories went online this week. This is the result of working with commercial laboratories to expand the scope of testing.

Michel Pense has said that priority will be given to medical and emergency workers, "who are there and who are affected by the new coronavirus. " He added that Americans over 65 with cough, fever or other symptoms are also a high priority. But on the front lines of the fight against the new coronavirus, some hospital staff said they did not feel "prioritized" for the time being.

A registered nurse in New Hampshire said her hospital staff did not have N95 masks, forcing them to reuse the old ones. There are also cases of patients who have recently tested positive and have not followed proper safety procedures when they walk from the emergency room to the hospital ward for treatment. "All the doctors and nurses are in contact with patients, " said the veteran nurse, who has worked for 28 years and asked not to be named for fear of reprisals. If someone tests positive, then many of us will have to be isolated in our homes for two weeks and we are already starting to run out of people."

FIGURE | CDC reports first staff confirmed diagnosis (Source: CDC. Com)

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
The CDC announced on March 15 that a staff member had been infected with the new coronavirus, the agency's first case. But the CDC said the employee, who tested positive for the new coronavirus, was "in good condition and has been quarantined to prevent transmission to others. " Other employees at the same unit are working remotely, the statement added, the office is also undergoing a deep cleaning. The CDC said it would not disclose more details about the case or any subsequent cases because of privacy concerns.

In addition, as of 5:00 a.m. on March 16, the Department of Defense had reported 37 confirmed cases of new pneumonia, said Jonathan Rath Hoffman, a Pentagon spokesman and Assistant Secretary of Public Affairs. This includes 18 military personnel, 13 dependants, 3 civilians and 3 contractor personnel. As of the previous morning, the Department of Defense had tested 495 people for the new coronavirus, the spokesman said. United States Secretary of Defense Mark Esper will be quarantined from his deputies and other staff to prevent the spread of the new coronavirus.

WORST CASE SCENARIO: 214 million Americans infected and 1.7 million killed

What is the worst that can happen in the United States if aggressive action is not taken to slow the spread of the new coronavirus from person to person?

Disease modelers at the U.S. CDC estimate that as many as 65 percent of Americans could end up with the new coronavirus, according to the New York Times. According to the report, the CDC shared its model with 50 teams of experts, all of whom worked hard to estimate how fast the virus was spreading and the severity of the cases it caused.

The worst-case numbers reflect the rapid human-to-human spread of the virus if nothing is done to slow its spread. If this mode of transmission is not controlled, then every person infected with the virus may infect two or three other people, resulting in increased infectivity. Of course, it is important to note that modelling the true course of a pandemic depends on broader and more accurate scientific information and must take into account the effectiveness of responses and issues such as the availability of medical equipment.

According to The Times, the CDC estimates that between 2.4 million and 21 million people could end up in hospitals in the United States, with critical care patients "crowding" the nation's emergency and intensive care units. In some models, the final death toll in the United States could be 200,000 to 1.7 million. That compares with about 30,000 deaths a year in the United States.

Store shelves are empty and shoppers are stocking up (source: MIT Technology Review) 

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
On March 15th President Donald Trump called on Americans to stop hoarding groceries and other goods, "You don't have to buy that much. Just take your time and relax, " DONALD TRUMP assured the Americans after talking to managers at major grocery chains, the grocery store will stay open, and the supply chain will stay healthy. But before Donald Trump's comments, Dr. Antony Foutch, the chief government infectious disease specialist and director of the NIH's National Allergy and Institute of Medical Science, said: He would like to see more aggressive controls, such as a 14-day national shutdown, which would require Americans to stay indoors as much as possible to help slow the spread of the new coronavirus.

"You can't win with an epidemic, " IRA Longini, one of the experts at the C.D.C. , told reporters. "If you go too far, it's scary. If you go wrong, people look down on you. So you have to be careful. "

The historic "TRIFECTA" of circuit breakers in six trading days may have given Trans some real cause for alarm. On the afternoon of March 16, he held a briefing at the White House to announce guidelines for dealing with the new outbreak of pneumonia. He advised people to avoid gatherings of more than 10 people and to stay away from public places such as bars and restaurants. In addition, minimize travel. The guidelines also require states where community infections have occurred to close bars, restaurants and other public facilities, but this is not a mandatory measure.

Donald Trump also said for the first time: "The U.S. economy is likely to have a recession, but for now, controlling the spread of the epidemic in the first place is the focus of all levels of U.S. government. " Stocks in the U.S. plunged nearly 13 percent, donald Trump's "racist nerve" seems to have been piqued by the record fall of nearly three decades. He called the new coronavirus "Chinese Virus" on Twitter, eliciting a furious response from many, and comments after its status were "split" and "extreme. ".

Any kind of virus should not be a country's problem, but the whole world, the whole human problem. In particular, after the World Health Organization Organization declared the new coronavirus a "global pandemic" , the new coronavirus epidemic has become a common global problem.

Governments should take responsibility for their own response, "blame" can not control the spread of the epidemic, also can not stop the economic downturn. Only keep a rational attitude, and actively and scientifically arrange the prevention and control measures to deal with the epidemic situation, is the most powerful response to the new coronavirus.
